# Git Commits

Only create commits when the user explicitly asks. If unclear, ask first.

## Git Safety

- NEVER update git config
- NEVER run destructive git commands (force push, hard reset, etc.) unless explicitly requested
- NEVER push, this will be done by the user, if necessary.
- NEVER skip hooks (`--no-verify`, `--no-gpg-sign`, etc.) unless explicitly requested
- NEVER force push to main/master — warn the user if they request it
- NEVER commit files that likely contain secrets (`.env`, credentials, etc.)
- NEVER add `Co-authored-by` lines (including Cursor/agent co-author trailers)

## Before Committing

Run in parallel:

- `git status` — untracked and modified files
- `git diff` and `git diff --cached` — staged and unstaged changes
- `git log` — recent messages to match repo style

Review all changes. Stage only files that belong in the commit.

## Commit Message Format

Use a HEREDOC for the message:

```bash
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
Subject line in imperative mood.

A few sentences or more (depending on how many changes there were) explaining
why the change was made and what it accomplishes. Focus on intent, not a file
list. However be detailed enough that someone reading would understand why
the change/commit was made.

https://genesyscs.atlassian.net/browse/CP-XXXX
EOF
)"
```

Rules:

- **Subject:** imperative, concise, describes the change (e.g. "Add X", "Split Y into Z")
  - Does not end with a period
  - Must fit as a Git commit subject title
- **Body:** optional but preferred for non-trivial changes; explain why, not just what
- **Story link:** include the Jira URL on its own line when work is tied to a ticket;
  omit when there is no ticket
  - Story number may be in the branch name (format BRANCH_TYPE/CP-STORYNUMBER-extra-info,
    i.e. feature/cp-123-info, cp-123 is the story)
  - If story is unknown, ask for the story.
  - If no story, do not add the story link line.
  - If Jira story add the link https://genesyscs.atlassian.net/browse/CP-XXXX, otherwise
    simply add the ID.
  - **No co-author trailers** — do not append `Co-authored-by:` lines

## Commit Scope

- One logical change per commit — split unrelated work into separate commits
- Cross-repo changes get separate commits in each repo
- Do not commit local-only config (dev paths, personal overrides) unless the user
  explicitly wants them tracked
- Do not create empty commits when there are no changes

## Amend Rules

Use `git commit --amend` ONLY when ALL are true:

1. User explicitly requested amend, OR pre-commit hook auto-modified files after a
   successful commit
2. HEAD commit was created by you in this conversation
3. Commit has NOT been pushed to remote

If a commit failed or was rejected by a hook, fix the issue and create a NEW commit.

## After Committing

Run `git status` to verify success. Do not push unless the user explicitly asks.
